Recap

useful functions:
head() : only shows the first 6 elements, i.e. if you have a large data frame, you can quickly check header and the first entries (analoguously: tail() )
paste( , sep=’’) : appends characters or numbers - great for working directories, loops across many maps or data.frames etc
data formats and access:
data.frame : [row, column] or “dollar sign”, i.e. mydata[1,2]: first row, second column, or mydata$MyColumnName[1]
matrix : see above
list : [[element]], i.e. mylist[[1]]. Achtung! A list element can consist of a data.frame, that you can then access like that: mylist[[1]][1,2]….
S4-objects (like spatial data) : @, i.e. RasterLayer@data@values



Data Types

Raster data

Data import

# read the ascii file as raster
# ras1 = mean annual temp * 10 stored as integer, not float
ras1 <- raster(x = paste(maps_wd, '/bio_asc_01.asc', sep = ''))
# ras1 - check description

Assign the projection

(crs - coordinate reference system) …@crs is the characteristic of the object (here: raster layer) Bor_mat, and … -> CRS() is calling to a function that sets the crs of the object. Mind the spelling in small letters/ capitals! crs = coordinate reference system CRS creates projection and sets arguments for crs!

An easy way to specify the crs is using the EPSG code, e.g. CRS(“+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84”) OR CRS(“+init=epsg:4326”). See http://spatialreference.org/. The code for WGS84 is 4326:

ras1@crs <- CRS(projargs = "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84")# equal to
ras1@crs <- CRS("+init=epsg:4326")
# mind: crs != CRS

Projections can also be transferred from one object to another, when the crs hasn’t yet been specified/ set (in which case, a spatial transform would be necessary). In the follwoing, load the topographic map (digital elevation model) of Borneo (Bor_dem.asc) and assign it the same crs as Bor_mat:

# digital elevation model
ras24 <- raster(x = paste(maps_wd, '/bio_asc_24.asc', sep = '')) #DEM
ras24@crs <- ras1@crs # same as: CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84")

Terrain computation - Create a hillshade (3D look)

  • simulates a 3D surface
  • computes shaded relief values for a raster surface
slope <- terrain(x = ras24, opt = "slope",
                    unit = "radians", neighbors = 8)
aspect <- terrain(x = ras24, opt = "aspect",
                     unit = "radians", neighbors = 8)
Bor_hs <- hillShade(slope, aspect, angle = 45,
                      direction = 270)

Plot the hillshade

plot(Bor_hs, col=grey(0:100/100), legend=FALSE)

and add colors on top: alpha value gives semi-transparency

plot(Bor_hs, col=grey(0:100/100), legend=FALSE)
plot(ras24, col=terrain.colors(25,alpha=0.3),add=T)
points(coordinates(ras1_cr),cex=0.1,pch='+')
plot(extent(ras1_cr),add=T, col='red')

Raster projection

Project the Grid (the small one!!!)

proj_moll=CRS("+proj=moll +lat_0=65 +lon_0=10") # Mollweide
Bor_dem_moll <-projectRaster(ras1_cr,crs=proj_moll)
persp(Bor_dem_moll, xlab="Easting", ylab="Northing",
      zlab="elevation", main="Elevation model of Borneo",
      r=1, d=5.5, expand=0.1, ticktype="detailed")

Working with stacks

#- We can assign each single raster a projection with just one command!
predictors <- stack(x = files.full[c(9, 12, 22, 24)])
projection(x = predictors) # crs(predictors)
## [1] NA
projection(x = predictors) <- CRS(projargs = "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84")

Data export

Save the hillshade raster (not the plot…)

#- define the workspace where to save - but remember that you change the working directory with that!
#- Better: store path within the file name (see point data example)
setwd(dir = output_wd)
#- save the data
writeRaster(x = Bor_hs, 
            filename = "hillshade.asc", 
            format = "ascii",
            overwrite = TRUE, 
            NAflag = -9999)
#- set back working directory
setwd(dir = work_wd)

# convert ras1 to degree Celsius units (divide by 10)

range(values(mean.t.c), na.rm = TRUE)
## [1]  6.3 27.8
# find areas with mean annual temp >= 25 deg C
mean.t.c.25 <- mean.t.c >= 25

plot(x = mean.t.c.25)

Accessing cell values of a raster I

Remember the function extract()

cells <- cellFromRowCol(object = ras1_cr, row = 5, col = 1:3)
cells    #gives cell ID number!!!
## [1] 121 122 123
extract(x = ras1_cr, y = cells) # gives cell values!
## [1] 266 265 266
plot(x = ras1_cr)
points(x = coordinates(obj = ras1_cr)[cells,], col = 'blue')

extract rastervalues from all rasters at once

This is very important if you want to create your master table, i.e. based on the xy-coordinates of your species sighting, you could extract the important environmental predictors at that location.

pred_dat <-   extract(predictors, cells) 
pred_dat
##      bio_asc_07 bio_asc_10 bio_asc_21 bio_asc_24
## [1,]         NA         NA         NA         NA
## [2,]         NA         NA         NA         NA
## [3,]         NA         NA         NA         NA
test <- data.frame(cells,pred_dat)
test
##   cells bio_asc_07 bio_asc_10 bio_asc_21 bio_asc_24

## 2   122         NA         NA         NA         NA
## 3   123         NA         NA         NA         NA
